subsection.p:
The pattern here shows that \ln(2) can be approximated by the partial sums of the infinite series
\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} (-1)^{k+1} \frac{1}{k}
where the alternating signs are indicated by the factor (-1)^{k+1}. We call such a series an alternating series. alternating series

Recall that the sequence of partial sums oscillates around the sum S so that

  \left|S - S_n \right| \lt  \left| S_{n+1} - S_n \right| = a_{n+1}
.

statement.p:
Determine how well the 100th partial sum S_{100} of

  \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \frac{(-1)^{k+1}}{k}

approximates the sum of the series.
